text.tspan: Quantifies the probability of ending at a node
while following a random walk along the graph
This can be seen as a modified version of the eigenvector centrality
that uses a weighted and normalized adjacency matrix that typically
only makes sense for directed graph.
Mathematically "the same", but in practice the assumption of directionality has consequence!
While the random walk algorithm can always be computed and lead to a result, the eigenvector centrality might not be decidable
if eigevalue is degenerate, no way of knowing which eigenvector to choose.
In other words, pagerank can always be computed, eiv centrality requires unidrectionality to be definite. However, PR on undirected
graph requires to make the assumption of directionality equily shared among partner nodes.
Quantifies how much a node is connected
